BRCA1 and BRCA2 encode proteins that orchestrate HRR, an error‑free repair pathway for DNA double‑strand breaks (DSBs). BRCA1 promotes end resection and recruitment of RAD51, while BRCA2 loads RAD51 onto single‑stranded DNA to form nucleoprotein filaments essential for strand invasion. Loss‑of‑function mutations (missense, nonsense, or frameshift) in either gene disrupt these processes, forcing cells to rely on error‑prone non‑homologous end joining (NHEJ) or micro‑homology–mediated end joining, leading to genomic instability and malignant transformation. Clinically, BRCA‑associated breast/ovarian cancers exhibit characteristic “BRCAness” signatures and are highly sensitive to poly(ADP‑ribose) polymerase (PARP) inhibitors (olaparib, rucaparib), which trap PARP at single‑strand breaks, converting them into lethal DSBs that cannot be repaired in BRCA‑deficient cells. Recent phase III trials (e.g., OlympiA) showed that adjuvant olaparib prolongs disease‑free survival in HER2‑negative early breast cancer with germline BRCA mutations. Additionally, synthetic lethality screens have identified that inhibition of DNA‑damage response kinases (ATM, ATR) further exploits HR deficiencies.  
**Summary:** BRCA1/2 loss cripples HRR, leading to reliance on faulty NHEJ;
